{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01J8WoatuKQdFu4u19AVZ43t","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see. The rule_stack is used to track the current rule being parsed. When we have:\n1. A <- B(T)\n2. B(X) <- C(X)\n\nWhen parsing A:\n- rule_stack = [A]\n- When we encounter B(T), we push A's parameters to args stack\n- Then we call B which pushes B to rule_stack and B's parameters\n\nThe issue is in Reference::parse_core at line 2563:\n```cpp\nFindReference vis(c.top_args(), c.rule_stack.back()->params);\n```\n\nThis uses the current rule's parameters (rule_stack.back()->params), but at this point rule_stack.back() is still the calling rule (e.g., A), not the macro being called (B).\n\nActually, looking more carefully - when we enter Reference::parse_core for B(T):\n- rule_stack.back() is A (the rule that called B)\n- We want to replace macro arguments with the actual values passed\n\nSo when B(T) is called:\n- We should use B's parameters (X) to match against T\n- But we're using A's parameters instead\n\nLet me check if there's a params member on the Reference object itself. Looking back at the Reference class:\n- It has `args_` which are the arguments passed to the macro\n- It has `is_macro_` flag\n- It has `rule_` which is the Definition being referenced\n\nSo the bug is: at line 2563, instead of using c.rule_stack.back()->params (the current/calling rule's params), we should be using rule_->params (the macro being called's params).\n\nLet me verify this is indeed the issue by looking at what rule_->params would be.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":7,"cache_creation_input_tokens":473,"cache_read_input_tokens":56297,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":473},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null}