    if (rule_->is_macro) {\n      // Macro\n      FindReference vis(c.top_args(), c.rule_stack.back()->params);\n\n      // Collect arguments\n      std::vector<std::shared_ptr<Ope>> args;\n      for (auto arg : args_) {\n        arg->accept(vis);\n        args.emplace_back(std::move(vis.found_ope));\n      }\n\n      c.push_args(std::move(args));\n      auto se = make_scope_exit([&]() { c.pop_args(); });\n      auto ope = get_core_operator();\n      return ope->parse(s, n, sv, c, dt);\n    } else {\n      // Definition\n      c.push_args(std::vector<std::shared_ptr<Ope>>());\n      auto se = make_scope_exit([&]() { c.pop_args(); });\n      auto ope = get_core_operator();\n      return ope->parse(s, n, sv, c, dt);\n    }\n  } else {\n    // Reference parameter in macro\n    const auto &args = c.top_args();\n    return args[iarg_]->parse(s, n, sv, c, dt);\n  }\n}\n\ninline std::shared_ptr<Ope> Reference::get_core_operator() const {","numLines":35,"startLine":2556,"totalLines":3856}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_011qrR3of8nbaUMaNEkT7N27","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see it clearly. Look at line 2563:\n\n```cpp\nFindReference vis(c.top_args(), c.rule_stack.back()->params);\n```\n\nThis creates a FindReference visitor with:\n- args_ = c.top_args() (the arguments pushed to the current context)\n- params_ = c.rule_stack.back()->params (the parameters of the CURRENT rule being parsed)\n\nBut this is wrong! When we have a macro call like B(T) in a non-macro rule A:\n- c.rule_stack.back() = A's Definition\n- A.params = [] (A is not a macro)\n- rule_ = B's Definition\n- rule_->params = [X] (B is a macro)\n\nThe issue is that we should be using rule_->params (the parameters of the macro being CALLED), not c.rule_stack.back()->params (the parameters of the current rule).\n\nThen in FindReference::visit(Reference &ope) at lines 2842-2846:\n```cpp\nfor (size_t i = 0; i < args_.size(); i++) {\n  const auto &name = params_[i];\n  if (name == ope.name_) {\n    found_ope = args_[i];\n    return;\n  }\n}\n```\n\nIf args_.size() > params_.size(), this accesses params_[i] out of bounds!\n\nIn the nested macro case:\n- A <- B(T)\n- B(X) <- C(X)\n- C(Y) <- Y\n\nWhen A calls B(T):\n- args_ = [T] (size 1)\n- params_ = [] (A has no parameters, size 0)\n- The loop tries to access params_[0], which is out of bounds!\n\nThis causes a memory error/segmentation fault.\n\nThe fix is simple: on line 2563, change from:\n\n\n```cpp\nFindReference vis(c.top_args(), c.rule_stack.back()->params);\n```\n\nto:\n```cpp\nFindReference vis(c.top_args(), rule_->params);\n```\n\nThis ensures that we use the parameters of the macro being called, which will match the size of the arguments being passed.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":7,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1818,"cache_read_input_tokens":66271,"cache_creation":{