ment value\n13. After matching X to T, args becomes [T]\n14. c.push_args([T]) sets up the context for parsing C's body\n15. When parsing Y (a reference to C's parameter), rule_ is nullptr since Y is a parameter, not a rule\n16. The code retrieves args[iarg_] where iarg_ was determined during LinkReferences - Y is at index 0 in C's params, so iarg_ = 0\n17. This returns args[0]->parse(...) to parse 'val'\n\nThe logic appears sound. Where's the actual problem?\n\nActually, I need to reconsider the initial setup. When A calls B(T), the arguments are [T], but c.top_args() is still empty before visiting those arguments. The FindReference visitor is called with c.top_args() = [] and c.rule_stack.back()->params = [X], which seems incorrect - it should have access to the current arguments being processed. Looking at lines 2563-2570, the order matters: arguments are visited first with FindReference, then pushed onto the context stack afterward.\n\nThe real issue emerges when arguments themselves contain macro parameters. If A were parameterized and T were one of A's parameters, then visiting T with FindReference([], [X]) would fail to resolve it properly since the current context has no parameters to match against.\n\nThe visitor substitutes macro parameters in argument expressions before passing them down the call chain. When B(X) calls C(X), the system needs to track what X represents at each level—whether it's a concrete type passed in or a parameter from an enclosing macro. The challenge is ensuring parameters get resolved correctly through nested macro expansions. seems right so far. But I need to trace through what actually happens with the rule_stack during nested macro calls. When parsing a rule's body, the rule gets pushed onto the stack at line 2496, then popped after parsing completes. So if I'm inside multiple nested rules, the stack will have multiple entries. At line 2563 in Reference::parse_core, when I'm resolving a reference, the rule_stack contains all the active rules in the call chain. This is where the out-of-bounds access likely occurs—when accessing rule_stack.back()->params with an index that's valid for one rule but not another in the nesting hierarchy. 's position in C.params is 0, so it returns args[0]->parse(...), which is T's parse function.\n\nThis logic appears sound, but I need to identify where the out-of-bounds access actually occurs. Looking back at the FindReference::visit loop, there's a potential issue if args_.size() doesn't match params_.size(). When FindReference is constructed at line 2563 with c.top_args() and c.rule_stack.back()->params, a mismatch between argument count and parameter count could cause the loop to access invalid indices.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":7,"cache_creation_input_tokens":365,"cache_read_input_tokens":68823,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":365},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7bbe0357-5a81-44ba-b67d-d1dfa22d5642","uuid":"cbb28e13-b4da-4bb5-af8b-693c8d869ee0"}
