{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01R64AJPzKAWnGji7vZ8Ncca","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good! So args_stack is resized to 1 at line 883, which means it has one empty vector initially. So top_args() will return the first (empty) vector initially.\n\nNow let me think about when we have a non-macro rule calling a macro:\n\nWhen A calls B(T):\n1. rule_stack = [A]\n2. args_stack = [empty vector]\n3. Reference::parse_core for B(T)\n4. Line 2563: FindReference vis(c.top_args(), c.rule_stack.back()->params)\n   - c.top_args() = [] (empty vector)\n   - c.rule_stack.back()->params = [] (A has no parameters)\n   - args_ = [], params_ = []\n5. Line 2567: for (auto arg : args_) with args_ = [T]\n   - arg = T (a Reference or Literal)\n   - arg->accept(vis) calls FindReference::visit\n6. FindReference::visit depends on the type of arg\n   - If T is a Literal, it returns T unchanged\n   - If T is a Reference, it checks if T is in params_\n     - params_ = [], so the loop at line 2842 runs with:\n       - for (size_t i = 0; i < 1; i++) {  // args_.size() = 1 (c.top_args() = [])\n         - Wait, args_ is created from c.top_args(), which is []\n         - So args_.size() = 0\n         - Loop doesn't execute\n\nHmm, wait. I'm confusing myself again. Let me re-read the FindReference constructor at line 2079-2081:\n\n```cpp\nFindReference(const std::vector<std::shared_ptr<Ope>> &args,\n              const std::vector<std::string> &params)\n    : args_(args), params_(params) {}\n\n\n```\n\nSo args_ and params_ are references to the vectors passed in. When A calls B(T), args_ points to the empty top_args() and params_ points to A's empty parameter list. When B then calls C(X), args_ points to [T] and params_ points to B's parameters [X]. The visitor checks if X matches any parameter in params_, and if so, replaces it with the corresponding argument from args_.\n\nNow I'm considering what happens if there's a mismatch between argument and parameter counts. If A calls B(T, U) but B only declares one parameter X, then args_ would be [T, U] while params_ would be [X]. The loop would only iterate once since params_.size() = 1, so U wouldn't get substituted. This could lead to U remaining unchanged in the output, which might not be the intended behavior.\n\n```\nA <- B(T, U)  // 2 arguments\nB(X) <- C(X)  // 1 parameter\n```\n\nWhen B calls C(X), the args_ stack contains [T, U] but params_ only has [X]. If the loop condition uses args_.size() instead of params_.size(), it would try to access params_[1], causing an out-of-bounds access. This is the actual bug—the loop iterates based on the wrong size, leading to accessing undefined memory when there are more arguments than parameters in a nested macro call. When B(T) is processed, the rule stack shows A as current with empty args, so the visitor gets no substitutions. After pushing [T], the stack becomes [[], [T]].\n\nWhen parsing B(X) <- C(X), rule_stack.back() is now B with c.top_args() = [T]. The visitor matches X against B.params[0] and replaces it with T. After another push, args_stack = [[], [T], [T]].\n\nWhen B invokes C, the args and params alignment needs to be checked against this nested state. c.top_args() = [T], so args[0] is a Reference to rule T. Calling parse on it delegates to T's rule, which matches 'val'.\n\nThe logic appears sound, so the SIGSEGV likely stems from an out-of-bounds access in FindReference::visit when args_.size() exceeds params_.size(). In the \"Nested macro call\" test, I need to trace whether this condition ever occurs during the parse(\"val\") call.\n\nWhen A invokes B(T), the args aren't pushed to the stack until after they're collected at lines 2572-2573. During the argument visitation at lines 2567-2570, args_stack still holds its initial empty vector, so c.top_args() returns []. FindReference receives empty args and params, the loop skips, and found_ope becomes T—no issue there.\n\nWhen B then calls C(X):\n- args_stack contains [[], [T]]\n- c.top_args() yields [T]\n- c.rule_stack.back()->params holds [X]\n- FindReference gets initialized with args_=[T] and params_=[X]\n- During visitation of X, the loop executes once, params_[0] matches \"X\", and args_[0] is returned correctly\n\nThe actual problem emerges in the loop condition itself. The code iterates while i < args_.size() but accesses params_[i] without verifying i < params_.size(). When args_.size() exceeds params_.size(), this causes an out-of-bounds access. In the test case, I need to determine if this mismatch actually occurs when non-macro rules invoke macros with mismatched argument counts. a template or shared_ptr reference issue. Looking at the FindReference struct definition, both args_ and params_ are stored as const references rather than copies. This means args_ points to c.top_args() and params_ points to c.rule_stack.back()->params. If either of these underlying vectors gets modified or destroyed after the visitor is created, we'd have a dangling reference problem. The concern is whether the rule stack or args stack could change during the traversal that uses these references.\n\nExamining the actual usage at lines 2563-2570, the FindReference visitor is created and used immediately without any intervening operations that would modify the rule stack, so the references should remain valid. The real issue appears to be the missing bounds check in the loop—we need to ensure both i < args_.size() and i < params_.size() before accessing either vector.\n\nHowever, the fundamental problem is that FindReference is initialized with c.rule_stack.back()->params when it should use rule_->params instead. The macro being called has its own parameter list, and we need to match against those specific parameters when substituting arguments, not the parameters of whatever rule happens to be on top of the stack during parsing.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,